procedures:
Annotation: Genomic features associated with peaks are obtained using ChIPseeker, an R package. Informative annotations include, but not limited to, genes and cis-regulatory elements near identified peaks.
Visualization: Tools such as deeptools can be used to visualize the enrichment profile of peaks around transcription start sites (TSSs).
Functional analysis of peaks: To study the biological relevance of enriched regions associated with a histone or transcription factor, various downstream analyses can be done using annotations from 78a. Though a detailed overview is beyond the scope of this protocol, here are some examples:
It is useful to find biological themes (e.g., pathways, molecular function etc.) associated with enriched regions. Databases such as GO (http://geneontology.org/[href=http://geneontology.org/]), REACTOME (https://reactome.org/[href=https://reactome.org/]) and KEGG (https://www.genome.jp/kegg/[href=https://www.genome.jp/kegg/]) can be queried to find overrepresented "terms" (set of genes associated with a function or pathway) within the annotated gene lists;
Motif enrichment analysis;
Various differential analyses to compare CUT&Tag libraries (e.g., WT vs KO).
